#X text 282 166 By default we have a single reference point of MIDI pitch 60 (C4) and a tracking amount of 100%. This means that C4 outputs a ratio of 1 and C5 outputs an octave higher (a ratio of 2) and C3 outputs an octave below (a 0.5 ratio)!, f 50;
#X text 282 232 A tracking of 50% means that an octave higher is half an octave \, so we have a ratio that is equal to the square root of 2 and a 200% tracking gives us a ratio of 4 (2 octaves)!, f 50;
#X msg 68 223 ref 48;
#X msg 76 250 ref 48 60;
#X msg 57 195 ref 60;
#X text 282 284 You can change the reference point with the 'ref' message or '-ref' flag with up to 2 values. If you have 2 values like '48 60' \, then you have a range from 40 to 60 where the output is always 1! Values above 60 get tracked according to this upper reference point and values below get tracked according to the lower reference point. A single value sets both the lower and upper references., f 50;
